Secondly, there is a volume in the British Museum, Additional MSS. 21, 974, which appears by the arms emblazoned on two leaves to have belonged to John Longland, Bishop of Lincoln, loro-1547, and whichI have quoted as giving the Lincoln Oolours, Vol. i. p. xxi.

The volume contains the variations to be made at Pontifical celebration of the Mass, and the Benedictions of Archbishop Peokham. The Use of the Ohurch for which this volume was written was the Sarum. There seems no doubt that these arms are those of Bishop Longland‚ and the only explanation Ι can suggestis, either that this volume was copied from one belonging to the Bishop of a Diooese whose Use really was Sarum, without proper adaptation to the Diooese in which it was to be used, or that,

in the beginning of the 16th Century, the Sarum Use either had been or was intended to be adopted in the Diooese of Linooln.

Usu OF BANGOR.

The Missal Offices contained in the Pontifical of Amanus, Bishop of Bangor, sn. 1268, are given in Appendix VIII. This Pontifical contains—

1. Offices strictly Episcopal. 2. Offioes which would be found in the Missal: these are given in the Appendix. 3, Offices which would be found in the Manual— (1) Baptism. (2) Matrimony. (3) For the Siok and Dying, and for the Burial of the Dead,
